'''Vernix caseosa''', also known as '''vernix''', is the waxy or [[cheese]]-like white substance found coating the [[skin]] of newborn human babies.  

==Etymology==
In [[Latin]], ''vernix'' means ''varnish'' and ''caseosa'' means ''cheesy''.

==Characteristics==
===Composition===
Vernix has a highly variable makeup but is primarily composed of [[sebum]], cells that have sloughed off the fetus's skin and shed [[lanugo]] hair.<ref name = Schachner2003>{{cite book |first1=Lawrence A. |last1=Schachner |first2=Ronald C. |last2=Hansen |title=Pediatric dermatology |publisher=Mosby |location=St. Louis |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-323-02611-6 |pages=206–7}}</ref>  12% of the dry weight of vernix is [[Branching (chemistry)|branched]]-chain [[fatty acid]]-containing [[lipids]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1203/PDR.0b013e318184d2e6 |title=Branched Chain Fatty Acids Are Constituents of the Normal Healthy Newborn Gastrointestinal Tract |year=2008 |last1=Ran-Ressler |first1=Rinat R |last2=Devapatla |first2=Srisatish |last3=Lawrence |first3=Peter |last4=Brenna |first4=J Thomas |journal=Pediatric Research |volume=64 |issue=6 |pages=605–9 |pmid=18614964 |pmc=2662770}}</ref> [[cholesterol]] and [[ceramide]].  Vernix of term infants has more [[squalene]] and a higher [[wax ester]] to [[sterol ester]] ratio than preterm infants.<ref name = Schachner2003/>

Comparison of lipid components of Vernix Caseosa, Stratum corneum and Skin surface (Sebaceous): <ref>Sumida Y, Yakumaru M, Tokitsu Y, et al. Studies on the function of Vernix caseosa: The secrecy of Baby's skin. Cannes, France: International Federation of the Societies of Cosmetic Chemists 20th International Conference; 1998. pp. 1–7.</ref><ref name=nskin>{{cite book|last=Hoath|first=Steven|title=Neonatal skin : structure and function|year=2003|publisher=Dekker|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=0-8247-0887-3|pages=193–208|edition=2. ed., rev. and expanded.}}</ref>
